{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d198375e-26f6-42ed-aab3-944d38e802ed","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but here's the general guidance:\n\n### Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump`. On macOS, use the OS-level crash reporting instead:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app.\n\n2. **Check for Apple crash reports** — macOS writes `.ips` / `.crash` files to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n3. **Retrieve the core file** — if `ulimit` was set, look for the core file at `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **If `/cores/` is empty**, ensure:\n   - The `/cores` directory exists and is writable (`sudo mkdir -p /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores`).\n   - SIP (System Integrity Protection) isn't blocking core dumps for your binary.\n   - On newer macOS, you may need to `codesign` your binary with the `com.apple.security.get-task-allow` entitlement.\n\n6. **Alternative — use `lldb` live** to attach and capture:\n   ```\n   lldb -p <pid>\n   (lldb) process save-core output.core\n   ```\n\nThe Apple `.ips` crash report alone often has enough info (faulting thread, backtrace, register state) for initial triage.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4011ef58-6a1d-4c84-a2c1-ddefb1eb7cf1","outputTokens":400,"requestId":"CB00:25F786:1F98ADE:22E2BD0:6A052A7B"},"id":"658c75d8-4189-459c-b589-5982207390b6","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:51:03.187Z","parentId":"1dce2813-dbbc-4cd9-8027-c2e906f30eca"}
